{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 20:35:02.099549", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Anomaly detected: Systematic ~1 second latency affecting all traffic to/from the DNS server (10.200.0.2), resulting in slow DNS name resolution for clients.\\n- Fault localization: dns_server, interface eth0.\\n- Root cause: Traffic control (tc) netem delay of 1 second configured on dns_server eth0.\\n\\nFindings and evidence\\n\\n1) Baseline connectivity and routing\\n- Hosts have valid DHCP-learned IPs and default routes:\\n  - host_1_1_1_1: 10.1.1.12/24 via 10.1.1.1\\n  - host_2_1_1_1: 10.2.1.10/24 via 10.2.1.1\\n- End-to-end IP reachability is healthy across the enterprise:\\n  - Pings between hosts and servers (e.g., 10.200.0.3 web_server_0, 10.200.0.7 load_balancer) show low RTT (typically ~1–5 ms) and 0% loss.\\n  - OSPF paths appear functional; there is no packet loss observed and latencies are consistent for non-DNS destinations.\\n\\n2) DNS resolution path and performance\\n- Both test hosts use the DNS server 10.200.0.2 exclusively:\\n  - /etc/resolv.conf on host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1: nameserver 10.200.0.2\\n- Pings to DNS server exhibit ~1004 ms RTT consistently:\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.2: avg ~1004 ms (4/4 received)\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.2: avg ~1003 ms (4/4 received)\\n  - Other servers -> 10.200.0.2: same pattern, often first ping ~2003 ms then ~1001 ms for subsequent probes.\\n- Curl timing from host_1_1_1_1 shows name lookup ~1.0 s, while connection and transfer after name resolution are fast:\\n  - http://web99.local: namelookup ~1.005 s; total ~2.10 s\\n  - http://web0.local: namelookup ~1.005 s; total ~2.00 s\\n  - Direct-to-IP requests are fast, confirming the delay is in DNS resolution:\\n    - http://10.200.0.7: total ~0.97–1.10 s (no name lookup)\\n    - http://10.200.0.3: total ~1.03–1.30 s (no name lookup)\\n\\n3) Traffic control/queuing disciplines\\n- dns_server eth0 has an explicit 1 second delay configured:\\n  - dns_server: tc qdisc show dev eth0\\n    - qdisc netem 805e: root refcnt 2 limit 1000 delay 1s\\n- server_access_router eth0 has a normal fq_codel, no added delay:\\n  - qdisc fq_codel 0: root … target 5ms interval 100ms …\\n\\nScope and impact\\n- All clients and servers that send traffic to 10.200.0.2 are incurring ~1 s extra latency per request/response. For DNS, this manifests as ~1 s added to each name resolution, degrading user-perceived web access times when using hostnames (but not when connecting by IP).\\n- No evidence of packet loss, routing failures, or issues with web servers or the load balancer. Web and server farm IP connectivity is normal.\\n\\nLocalization and root cause\\n- Faulty device: dns_server (10.200.0.2), interface eth0.\\n- Root cause: Misconfiguration of traffic control (netem delay 1s) on dns_server eth0, introducing an artificial 1 second delay to all egress (and effectively ingress) traffic on that interface.\\n\\nNo remediation steps are provided per request., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='dca16476-7fcd-414b-8dc9-e6c430289051'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
